```

@tigtms 

> I have needed to embed functionality (such as a third party WebRTC client into a frame) manually. Heaven knows how I would achieve this without being able to inspect the output, when I have no control on what is provided by a third party.

This kind of functionality is embedded using platform views, which are fully supported in our WebGL renderers. And yes, you can right click and inspect the contents of a platform view. If the view is all HTML provided by the third party, you'll see it.

> rendering of SVGs creating a clunky experience in non-chrome browsers hence the need to manage them manually at html level.

There are a few ways to render SVGs in Flutter Web, all supported by our WebGL renderers. Some are web-specific but provide all functionality offered by browsers. Others are limited but provide consistency across all platforms.

**Web-specific**

* [Draw the SVG into a canvas](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3768565/drawing-an-svg-file-on-a-html5-canvas). Then use [createImageFromTextureSource](https://api.flutter.dev/flutter/dart-ui_web/createImageFromTextureSource.html) to turn it into an `Image` object that Flutter can render.
* If the UI is made of _few_ large SVGs, you can embed them as `<svg>` tags using platform views. "Few" is the operative word here. Platform views should be used sparingly, as they have performance cost.

**Cross-platform**

The following packages sacrifice some SVG functionality, but work consistently across all platforms supported by Flutter:

* `package:flutter_svg` - implements a subset of SVG.
* `package:vector_graphics` - a vector graphics file format optimized for Flutter.

